(9548,'Configuring aliases for URLs','','none'),
(9549,'What is a URL?','','none'),
(9550,'URL is the abbreviation for \"Uniform Resource Locator\", which is the page\'s address on the web. It is the \"name\" by which a browser identifies a page to display. In the example \"Visit us at <em>example.com</em>.\", <em>https://example.com</em> would be the URL for the home page of your website. Users use URLs to locate content on the web.','','none'),
(9551,'What is a path?','','none'),
(9552,'A path is the unique, last part of the URL for a specific function or piece of content. For example, for a page whose full URL is <em>https://example.com/node/7</em>, the path is <em>node/7</em>. Here are some examples of paths you might find in your site:','','none'),
(9553,'node/7: Path to a particular content item.','','none'),
(9554,'taxonomy/term/6: Path to a taxonomy term page.','','none'),
(9555,'user/3: Path to a user profile page.','','none'),
(9556,'What is an alias?','','none'),
(9557,'The core software allows you to provide more understandable URLs for pages on your site, which are called <em>aliases</em>. For example, if you have an \"About Us\" page with the path <em>node/7</em>, you can set up an alias of <em>about</em> so that your visitors will see it as <em>https://www.example.com/about</em>.','','none'),
(9558,'Overview of configuring paths, aliases, and URLs','','none'),
(9559,'The core Path module provides the URL aliasing functionality. The contributed <a href=\"https://www.drupal.org/project/pathauto\">Pathauto</a> module allows you to configure automatically-generated URL aliases for content items and other pages. See the related topics listed below for specific tasks.','','none'),
